<BaseLayout
  title="ML Feature Importance Analyzer — Feature Importance Visualization Guide"
  description="Complete guide to machine learning feature importance: scikit-learn feature_importances_, SHAP values, permutation importance, mutual information, and visualization with matplotlib and seaborn."
  tool="ml-feature-importance-analyzer"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">ML Feature Importance Analyzer</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Understand which features drive your model predictions using scikit-learn importances, SHAP values, permutation importance, and mutual information.</p>
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ scikit-learn importances</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ SHAP values</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ permutation importance</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ mutual information</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Why Feature Importance Analysis Matters</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Feature importance analysis serves two distinct purposes: model understanding and feature selection. Understanding which features drive predictions helps you catch data leakage, validate that the model has learned sensible patterns (does it use clinically meaningful features?), build stakeholder trust, and debug unexpected behavior. Feature selection based on importance scores can reduce dimensionality, improve generalization, and speed up inference — especially important when collecting or computing certain features is expensive.</p>
  <p class="mb-4">No single importance metric is universally correct. Each method has assumptions and failure modes. Best practice is to compute multiple metrics and look for agreement — features that rank highly across Gini impurity, permutation importance, and SHAP are almost certainly important. Features that rank highly in only one metric deserve closer investigation.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">scikit-learn feature_importances_ (Gini Impurity)</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Tree-based models in scikit-learn expose <code>feature_importances_</code> after fitting. This measures the total reduction in impurity (Gini or MSE) attributable to each feature across all trees and all splits, normalized to sum to 1.0. It is fast, requires no additional computation, and generally provides a reasonable ranking of important features.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={sklearnImportanceExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Known limitations: high-cardinality features (many unique values) get artificially inflated importance because they offer more potential split points. Correlated features split importance between themselves, making each appear less important than they are. For these reasons, treat Gini importance as a quick first-pass filter, not a definitive ranking.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Permutation Importance</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Permutation importance directly measures predictive contribution by destroying a feature's relationship with the target via random shuffling. If a feature is truly important, shuffling its values should significantly hurt model performance. If performance barely changes, the feature is either unimportant or redundant with other features.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={permutationImportanceExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Key advantages: works with any scikit-learn estimator (not just trees), evaluates the exact metric you care about (AUC, F1, RMSE), and running on validation data reveals actual generalization importance rather than training-fit importance. The standard deviations across repeats indicate stability — high std means the importance estimate is noisy.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">SHAP Values — Gold Standard for Explainability</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) is the most theoretically rigorous approach to feature importance. Rooted in cooperative game theory, SHAP computes the marginal contribution of each feature by averaging its effect across all possible feature orderings. This satisfies important mathematical properties: efficiency (contributions sum to the prediction), symmetry (equivalent features get equal attribution), and consistency (removing an important feature never increases its measured importance).</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={shapExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">SHAP provides both global importance (mean absolute SHAP) and per-sample explanations. The beeswarm plot is the most information-dense visualization: each dot is one sample, x-position shows the SHAP value (impact on prediction), and color shows the feature value (red = high, blue = low). This immediately reveals the direction and magnitude of each feature's effect.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Mutual Information and Correlation Analysis</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Mutual information and correlation are model-agnostic metrics that measure the statistical relationship between each feature and the target variable directly, without training a model first. They are useful for fast initial filtering before training expensive models.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={mutualInfoExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Mutual information measures any statistical dependency, including non-linear relationships that correlation misses. A feature with high MI but low correlation likely has a non-linear relationship with the target — a strong signal that non-linear models (trees, neural networks) are needed.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Practical Feature Selection Workflow</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Step 1 — Correlation screening:</strong> Remove features with near-zero variance (<code>VarianceThreshold</code>) and check pairwise correlations. For groups of highly correlated features (r &gt; 0.9), keep one representative per group.</li>
    <li><strong>Step 2 — Quick mutual information filter:</strong> Rank all features by MI score and consider dropping features with MI ≈ 0 (statistically independent of target).</li>
    <li><strong>Step 3 — Train baseline model + Gini importance:</strong> Train a Random Forest and review feature_importances_. Identify the top 50–70% of features by cumulative importance.</li>
    <li><strong>Step 4 — Permutation importance validation:</strong> Run permutation importance on validation data. Features with importance ≤ 0 (shuffling them doesn't hurt) are candidates for removal.</li>
    <li><strong>Step 5 — SHAP for final interpretation:</strong> Compute SHAP values for the final feature set to understand direction and magnitude of effects. Use for model validation and stakeholder communication.</li>
    <li><strong>Step 6 — Ablation study:</strong> Train models with progressively smaller feature sets (top-20, top-10, top-5) and compare validation performance. The simplest model within 1–2% of full-feature performance is usually the right choice for production.</li>
  </ul>

